post_text:
Before you go to the polls today, we want you to know these important things:
-This vote will not increase school district taxes but will provide a dedicated funding source for these projects
-An approved Revenue Purpose Statement would enable the district to use SAVE funds for things like upgrading information technology infrastructure, purchasing or improving grounds, and remodeling, reconstructing, repairing, expanding, or improving school buildings. The district could also upgrade energy efficiency, furnish school facilities, and purchase transportation with these funds.

Please get out and vote today!
Go Rebels!

post_text: FYI: If your child is quarantined as a result of exposure or a positive COVID test, please notify the #SiouxCentral school nurse, the building secretary and/or building principal. This will activate the Sioux Central Distance Learning Support Team, and a member will reach out to you and/or your student. The team is in place to be a resource for you and your student during the time out of school and during the transition back to school. From basic technology support to gathering resources, the team serves as a home to school connection. Partnering with your student's teacher(s), the team is designed to support your student and their learning! #SiouxCentral

Elementary teachers will be contacting students/parents to set up Back to School Conferences in place of our traditional Open House. Press Release:
Spencer Chamber of Commerce and the Clay County Community Foundation have partnered in purchasing a
limited supply of pork loin roasts from Tyson Foods at a bargain rate and wish to distribute them to Clay County
households at no cost, while they last. The Clay County Community Foundation has taken on the task of getting a
portion of this meat into the rural communities. If you are a resident of one of these communities in Clay County
and have been impacted by the CoVid-19 Pandemic and could use a little help, please come to the distribution
location nearest you at the time listed. Please share this message with households that may not have seen it.

Peterson Community Center: Sunday, May 3 2:00-4:00
Webb Fire Station: Sunday, May 3 2:00-4:00

Please stay in your vehicle and the meat will be brought to you.

post_text:
Additional Update: From Rust's Western Shed in Storm Lake - All prom tuxedo rentals for Sioux Central's Prom on April 18th have been cancelled. We are waiting to hear if Prom will be moved to a new date. I will contact everyone if Prom is rescheduled to make sure that date works for you. If they can't find a new date a full refund will be available at the store when we reopen.

An update regarding Prom from Squire Shop in Spencer: All prom tuxedo rentals have been cancelled. Whomever has made a payment, I will keep on file so we do not need to recollect when a date is determined. If people would like a refund, they will need to call us and we can make arrangements for that. If they do get a refund, they will also have to call us back to reorder their rentals. Those that keep their money on file, we will automatically reserve their tuxedo for them.

post_text:
Sioux Central’s FLL teams competed on Saturday, December 7th in Estherville, Iowa. Two teams of students from Sioux Central ranging from 4th-8th grade represented Sioux Central at this regional competition.

One Sioux Central team, “The City Stompers”, walked away with 1st place with the Core Values Award. This award recognizes the team that shows the best at working together and recognizes each others ideas and opinions, and they come up with the best solutions to a problem.

The second Sioux Central team, “The Lego Clashers”, received the Champion Award. This award recognizes the team that scores in the top 25% of the core values award, the robot missions award, and the project award. They had to solve a problem that cities and towns face.

The Lego Clashers will compete at the state level in January at Iowa State University against 120 teams from across Iowa. They will be presenting to our 3rd-6th grade students at Sioux Central this Friday at 12:15 p.m. in the gym. Way to go Sioux Central’s FLL teams for a great job this season.

Each year we chose a service project to participate in. This year we have chose to support the Jaci Hermstad foundation. We have 6 buckets in our school office with teachers names on the buckets, the teacher who’s bucket has the most money in it by the end of the 3rd quarter of the homecoming game will participate in the ice bucket challenge in front of the stands in between the 3rd & 4th quarter of football game! The buckets will also be available at the homecoming game (September 27th) for those who can’t make it into the school to donate! ALL PROCEEDS GO TO SUPPORT THE JACI HERMSTAD FOUNDATION! post_text:
Preschool Scholarships

BVCS Early Childhood Iowa is offering preschool scholarships for children residing in Buena Vista, Crawford, and Sac Counties who are attending a 3 or 4 year old preschool program. BVCS Early Childhood Iowa may pay up to $150 a month for the scholarship. Applications will be processed and approved by financial need. Scholarship payments will begin in September or the month the completed application is received and approved. Parents are responsible for tuition payments until the application has been approved.

Awards will be made after the August 1st, 2019 deadline.

English application-
http://bvcsempowerment.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/EN-Preschool-Scholarship19-20.pdf
Spanish application-
http://bvcsempowerment.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/SP-Preschool-Scholarship19-20.pdf

post_text: Ben Hargens, a senior at Sioux Central and son of John and Karen Hargens, was awarded the BBB Student of Integrity Award and honored at the Better Business Bureaus' annual Torch Awards luncheon in Des Moines on April 23rd. Ben was one of 5 students recognized. Students were selected based on their commitment to honesty and accountability inside and outside of the classroom. Each student selected receives a $2500 scholarship towards their continuing education. Ben plans to attend South Dakota State University in the fall and major in Animal Science.

post_text: We are excited to announce that the Twins Community Fund Board of Directors, and the entire Minnesota Twins Baseball Club, have awarded a grant to be utilized by the Sioux Central Softball Team! The Twins program awarded Peterson Brooke Memorial Ball Fields a 2019 Twins Fields for Kids matching grant of $15,000. Peterson Brooke Memorial Field is the home of the Sioux Central Rebels. This grant will be used specifically for the purchase and installation of a new softball fence. The current fence was installed in 1999 when the field was built. We feel very fortunate to receive this generous grant from the Twins Community to update our current facility! https://www.mlb.com/twins

post_text: Heavy Rebel Hearts Today... Mrs. Dorene Ehlers, our ELL/TAG instructor passed away early this morning after her battle with cancer. Just a few weeks ago, Dorene e-mailed me and one of her comments was, "I am just really grateful for what I can do even with many limitations." This was how Dorene approached everything, with the most positive attitude. She was an inspiration to many. She will be so greatly missed by all who had the privilege of knowing her. We Love you Mrs. Ehlers! As soon as we know funeral arrangements, we will let you know.

post_text:
Upcoming Presentations at Sioux Central

Tuesday, March 26th

Career and College Planning at 6:00 in Room 243 (Business Room)

The goal of the evening Career and College Planning Program is to equip sophomores and their parents/guardians with the knowledge to select an appropriate college and understand the admission and scholarship application process. Attendees will leave knowing how colleges review transcript information such as GPA, ACT/SAT scores and high school course selection, as well as a timeline for success from junior year through graduation.

Financial Aid Program at 7:00 in Room 243 (Business Room)

The goal of the Financial Aid Program is to help high school juniors and their parents/guardians understand the process of applying for financial aid and scholarships, offer effective tools for college cost comparisons, and learn how they can access additional help. The following topics are covered during the presentation. FAFSA opens October 1st!

post_text: Mrs. Brown and her 7th graders celebrated National Pi Day! National Pi Day not only commemorates a very special number, but also celebrates the birthday of the great scientist and mathematician Albert Einstein. Pi was first calculated by Archimedes of Syracuse (287–212 BC), one of the greatest mathematicians of the ancient world. National Pi Day has become a day to celebrate numbers and math, and celebrations are held across the country in honor of this very special number.
